2. Our Main Result
The following immediate consequence of Theorem 2 is more suitable for our purposes.
Corollary 1. The Hultman number SH (n, k) is equal to the number of (n + 1)cycles q so that the product (12 · · · n(n + 1))q is a permutation with exactly k cycles, that is, c(Γ((12 · · · n(n + 1))q) = k.
Example 1. For any ﬁxed n, we have SH (n, n+1) = 1 since c(G(p)) = n+1 if and only if p is the identity permutation. And indeed, there is exactly one (n + 1)-cycle (in fact, one permutation) q ∈ Sn+1 so that (12.. · · · n(n + 1))q has n + 1 cycles, namely q = (12 · · · n(n + 1))−1 = (1(n + 1)n · · · 2).
In other words, ﬁnding the average of the numbers c(G(p)) over all n-permutations p is equivalent to ﬁnding the average of the numbers c(Γ((12.. · · · n(n + 1))q), where q is an (n + 1)-cycle.
Let us consider the product s = (12 · · · n)z, where z is a cycle of length n. Let us insert the entry n + 1 into z to get the permutation z′ so that n + 1 is inserted between two speciﬁc entries a and b in the following sense.
 z(i) if i ∈/ {a, n + 1},  z′(i) = n + 1 if i = a, and  b if i = n + 1.
