The following proposition is the ﬁrst step towards describing how the Hultman numbers grow. Proposition 1. Let a, b, and z′ be deﬁned as above, and let s′ = (12 · · · (n + 1)z′. Then we have
 c(Γ(s)) − 1 if 2 ≤ a, and a − 1 and z(1) are not in the same cycle of s,  c(Γ(s′) = c(Γ(s)) + 1 if 2 ≤ a, and a − 1 and z(1) are in the same cycle of s, and  c(Γ(s)) + 1 if a = 1.

