Proof. Let us assume ﬁrst that a ≥ 2, and that a−1 is in a cycle C1 of s, and z(1) is in a diﬀerent cycle C2 of s. Let C1 = ((a − 1)b · · · ) and let C2 = (z(1) · · · n). After the insertion of n + 1 into z, the newly obtained permutation s′ = (12.. · · · (n + 1)z′ sends a − 1 to n + 1, then n + 1 to z(1), then leaves the rest of C2 unchanged till its last entry. Then it sends n back to z′(n + 1) = b, from where it continues with the rest of C1 with no change. So in s′, the cycles C1 and C2 are united, the entry n + 1 joins their union, and there is no change to the other cycles of s. See Figure 2 for an illustration.
